        %p
          %small.muted
            Each piece is counted once for each orchestra that played it (repeat performances by the same orchestra are not counted).
    .row
      .col-md-9
        %p
          These histograms show a rather remarkable degree of confluence between the 7 orchestras. Taken together, there are 5 clear trends:

        %ul
          %li
            %b The Baroque Bump (1710s to 1740s)
          %li
            %b The Mozart-Beethoven Foothill (1780s to 1820s):
            Schubert probably plays a role here as well.
          %li
            %b The Mendelssohn-Schumann Spire (1840s)
          %li
            %b The Late Romantic to Post War Mountain (1870s to 1940s):
            This is the majority of most orchestras' repertoires.
          %li
            %b The Contemporary Comeback (2000s to 2010s):
            Driven largely by the LA Philharmonic, new works are much more popular than anything from the preceding few decades.
         
        %p Of all of the orchestras I looked at, New York Philharmonic has the most evenly distributed repertoire across different decades, and LA Philharmonic played the most new music (average year: 1886). Boston played the oldest (average year: 1873). What is surprising to me is how much this reflects my own musical tastes &mdash; I had thought I was fairly biased in the performances I chose to attend, but as it turns out, most of my choices come from the most popular 1870-1940 period.

    .row
      .col-md-9
        .page-header
          %h3 The Composers

        %p
          First, some troubling news: out of 530 distinct pieces performed, 6 were written by women (<i>barely</i> more than 1 percent).
          Five of those pieces are brand new (they had or will have premieres this season). If I may editorialize for a minute: this is <i>abysmal</i>.          Granted, it certainly looks like the field is making an effort to introduce new voices this season (five of those pieces are world premieres), but happens to those pieces next year?
          Various sources indicate the percentage of active composers who are female varies by country from around 10% to 25%.
          I know I'm not the first person to point this out.

